The aims and specific objectives of the study were as follows:
- to review the flood warning technologies currently available, and likely to be
available in the near future in relation to both fluvial and tidal flooding;
- to gather evidence on take-up, use of, and social performance of existing/recent and
recent/future technologies;
-  to analyse the information gathered in order to identify barriers to effective
communication and lessons to be learned;
- to identify the best way to use the various warning technologies to improve their
social performance in delivering the Agency’s flood warning service.
The emphasis of the research is on warnings to households and not to businesses.

The Corepoint project is based on pilot sites. The French pilot sites are the Mont-Saint-Michel bay and the gulf of Morbihan. These two places are presented in this document. The different aspects of this presentation are:
- The territory;
- The human activities;
- The current management tools;
- The management stakes of the territory.

This report provides an analysis of options to improve the planning and management of the
Wales Territorial Sea. The basic objectives and notes of the tender specification are
outlined below.
Objectives
· To review the current state of management of the Wales Territorial Sea (WTS) with
particular reference to:
- sea use geography;
- law;
- organisations involved;
- management dimensions of planning and development decisions;
- the European dimension;
- co-ordination among management organisations;
- an evaluation of territorial sea management in countries with relevant experience.
· To consider options for change, focusing upon:
- management strategies;
- decision-making;
- territorial sea management systems.
· To identify a preferred option and make recommendations

Overall objectives
1. To develop a coherent and realistic plan for the estuary’s flood defences that is:
• compatible with natural estuary processes;
• compatible with adjacent developments, including preferred options for adjoining lengths of frontage; and
Strategy objectives
Key issues
2. To ensure that all proposals are:
• compatible with natural estuary processes;
• technically feasible;
• economically viable;
• environmentally appropriate; and
• socially acceptable.
• sustainable, taking into account future changes in the environment (human, built or natural), in sea levels or in the climate.

This Directory has two principle purposes:

·	To provide a catalogue of ideas, which have been successful in contributing to sustainable management of the coast, for adaptation and use elsewhere;

·	To demonstrate the added value of integrated management, by focussing on outcomes (what changed because this work was done) as well as outputs (what did the initiative produce, e.g. a strategy, a code of practice). Outputs are meaningless if they do not make a difference.
